   <titles>
      <title>Invertible Linear Transformations</title>
      <plain.title>Invertible Transformations</plain.title>
   </titles>
   <intro>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>Here we discuss linear maps <math>
                     <latex>S\from \RNr[n]\to \RNr[n]</latex>
                  </math> whose transformation effect on space can be reversed. For example, rotating <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                  </math> through the angle <math>
                     <latex>\pi/2</latex>
                  </math> counter clockwise is a transformation which can be reversed: by the clockwise rotation through the angle <math>
                     <latex>\pi/2</latex>
                  </math>. In general, the transformation effect of  <math>
                     <latex>S\from \RNr[n]\to \RNr[n]</latex>
                  </math> can be reversed if there is a <math>
                     <latex>T\from \RNr[n]\to \RNr[n]</latex>
                  </math> such that <math>
                     <latex>T\Comp S(\Vect{x})=\Vect{x}</latex>
                  </math> for each <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                  </math> in <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
            <para>
               <para.body>We will see that a linear <math>
                     <latex>L\from \RNr[n]\to \RNr[n]</latex>
                  </math> is invertible exactly when its representing matrix <math>
                     <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                  </math> is invertible. In this case the inverse of <math>
                     <latex>L</latex>
                  </math> is represented by <math>
                     <latex>\Mtrx{A}^{-1}</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
   </intro>
